e new to their study. As scholars and teachers of early English, the contributors cover literary and cultural material from a range of genres within the Old English, Middle English, Tudor, and Stuart periods and collectively delve into a shared interest in facilitating what we might loosely define as “newcomer” or “non-specialist” encounters with the past: initial, exploratory contact in which prior knowledge cannot be assumed, whether involving creative professionals, experts from other disciplines, undergraduate and school students, or members of the public. Considering artworks and installation, theatre and performance and curation practices, case studies offer practice-based examples of learning and engagement which proceed primarily through creative and playful approaches. The case studies are arranged into two broad groups: those which work through performance and theatrical play of various kinds, and those which work through playful practices of production and making. All share a perspective of irreverence, of vivid immersion, and of the possibilities of conjuring with the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aEDUCATION / Teaching Methods & Materials / Arts & Humanities.2bisacsh  aPedagogies, creativity, medieval, early modern, early English literature, performance.1 aBrookman, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrookman, Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCavanagh, Sheila T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaddon, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKline, Daniel T., econtributor.4ctb4https:/